structure of deoxyribosenucleic acid (DNA)

70
00:05:57,030 --> 00:06:02,030
and (quoting from the Nobel committee’s
announcement) “its significance for information

71
00:06:02,030 --> 00:06:04,590
transfer in living material”.

72
00:06:04,590 --> 00:06:12,190
It was Rosalind Franklin’s famous x-ray
“photograph 51” of DNA crystal diffraction

73
00:06:12,190 --> 00:06:15,110
which provided the final clue to the structure.

74
00:06:15,110 --> 00:06:20,490
Franklin would sadly die of ovarian cancer
before the Nobel prize was awarded.

75
00:06:20,490 --> 00:06:25,290
DNA resides permanently within the nucleus
of a living cell.

76
00:06:25,290 --> 00:06:29,990
How then, is its information conveyed
to the rest of the cell and elsewhere in the

77
00:06:29,990 --> 00:06:36,090
organism; how is new living material subsequently
synthesized; and how do initial (“stem”)

78
00:06:36,090 --> 00:06:43,050
cells differentiate into specialized cells
as diverse as ganglions, muscle cells, or

79
00:06:43,050 --> 00:06:44,050
skin?

80
00:06:44,050 --> 00:06:48,210
Major steps towards answering these questions
were made in research that would result in

81
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:52,870
Nobel prizes in chemistry in 2006 and 2009.

82
00:06:52,870 --> 00:06:59,340
The first step in carrying out the commands
encoded in DNA is its transcription into so-called

83
00:06:59,340 --> 00:07:04,680
messenger-RNA, which then leaves the confines
of the nucleus to the protein-producing parts

84
00:07:04,680 --> 00:07:06,340
of the cell.

85
00:07:06,340 --> 00:07:12,710
How mRNA is synthesized and carries the genetic
information with high fidelity, via a very

86
00:07:12,710 --> 00:07:19,330
special macromolecule called RNA-polymerase,
was reported by Roger Kornberg and co-workers

87
00:07:19,330 --> 00:07:23,650
in 2001, for which he received the 2006 Nobel
prize in chemistry.

88
00:07:23,650 --> 00:07:32,290
The following step, that of protein synthesis,
uses the blueprint of the messenger RNA, plus

89
00:07:32,290 --> 00:07:38,940
raw material in the form of amino acids attached
to small transfer-RNA (tRNA) molecules in

90
00:07:38,940 --> 00:07:42,950
a chemical factory called the ribosome.

91
00:07:42,950 --> 00:07:47,240
The detailed description of the mechanisms
by which this highly complex biomolecular

92
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:54,390
process occurs won Ada Yonath, Thomas Steitz,
and Venkatraman Ramakrishnan the Nobel prize

93
00:07:54,390 --> 00:07:58,360
